		<header>
			
			<h1>Agriculture speculation and the EC raw materials communication </h1>

			
			<h4>
												01 March 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>According to press reports, the EC communication ‘Tackling the challenges in commodity markets and on raw materials’, has – at the insistence of the French government – included sections on ‘agriculture and security of food supply’. While the communication initially focused on securing critical minerals for European high-tech manufacturers, it now also includes proposals for ‘measures to improve the transparency of financial and commodity markets’. This needs to be seen in the context of the French Presidency of the G20, and mounting concern over the impact of financial speculation on agricultural commodity price developments.</p><p>In January 2011, EC officials in off-the-record press briefings argued that while attention has been paid to ‘soaring demand from emerging economies, decreasing yields due to unpredictable weather patterns and the impacts of bio-fuels production … the biggest problem is the link between agricultural markets and other commodity markets that have nothing to do with agriculture.’ It was maintained that agricultural prices were now being ‘affected by completely different things … financial markets are dragging prices up and down irrespective of agricultural realities.’</p><p>In the raw materials communication, the EC noted that the process of CAP reform had resulted in EU producers and traders now being ‘more exposed to market price developments’. This is thought to give rise to two issues: ‘security of food supply and the need for increased transparency on agricultural derivatives markets’. The former is likely to be reflected in the forthcoming 2013 round of CAP reforms, particularly since higher input costs are expected to squeeze farmers’ profit margins in the coming years, despite higher price levels. It is the need to increase transparency on agricultural derivatives markets which is the focus of proposals outlined in the raw materials communication.</p><p>The actions proposed primarily relate to improving market information. Commitments are therefore made to greater cooperation among member state authorities, and internationally to improving the quality and timeliness of market information and the situation regarding stock levels. This is seen as essential to ‘ensuring the proper functioning of the agri-food chain’. While it is acknowledged that getting to grips with the proper functioning of supply chains cannot deal with price volatility as such, it is held that it can address ‘the transmission of price developments throughout the supply chain’. The need for the EU and member states to ‘contribute to improved food market functioning at global, regional and national levels, including through improved market transparency’, is recognised.</p><p>Significantly, the communication also stresses ‘the need for improved governance and international dialogue’ over government actions which can ‘affect physical markets and cause price volatility’.</p><p>The impact of price volatility on the existing situation of under-investment in agriculture in many developing countries is recognised, with EU development policy recognising ‘the need to reverse this trend’. In this context, emphasis is placed on strengthening farmers’ organisations in developing countries ‘to improve price transparency, to increase agricultural productivity on a sustainable basis and to develop and apply regulatory frameworks’. Such initiatives it is held would ‘increase resilience and adaptability to food shocks’ in developing countries.</p><p>Against this background, the communication includes a variety of proposals to improve understanding of the impact of various forms of speculative investments on price volatility, by promoting transparency in the operation of these markets, and formalising this trade by bringing it more clearly within the scope of EU regulations. This is to be reflected in a range of existing and new regulations on financial services and the operation of financial product markets.</p>
		
		
