				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The communication implicitly recognises the wider relevance of the EU’s new policy initiatives in the dairy sector on strengthening the functioning of supply chains, (see <i>Agritrade </i>article ‘
<a href="http://agritrade.cta.int/en/Commodities/Dairy-sector/News/EC-milk-package-proposals-may-hold-lessons-for-other-sectors" target="_blank">EC “milk package” proposals may hold lessons for other sectors</a>’, January 2011). Indeed, the development of ACP-EU cooperation to strengthen the technical and policy capacities of ACP public authorities to strengthen the functioning of supply chains, so that agricultural producers are better placed to survive periods of price volatility, would appear to represent a major new area of potential collaboration. This applies not only to the functioning of domestic supply chains in ACP countries (see <i>Agritrade </i>article ‘
<a href="http://agritrade.cta.int/en/Commodities/Cotton-sector/News/Improving-the-functioning-of-the-supply-chain-seen-as-key-to-Tanzanian-cotton-sector-revival" target="_self">Improving the functioning of the supply chain seen as key to Tanzanian c...</a>’, March 2011), but also the functioning of ACP-EU supply chains, where inequalities in power relationships along the supply chain could give rise to abuse (including the slow transmission of price increases to primary producers).</p><p>The EU’s development policy recognition of the need to reverse under-investment in agriculture in developing countries (reiterated in the raw materials communication), needs to be reflected in National Indicative Programme allocations to the ACP agricultural sector. This is particularly the case regarding support for farmers’ organisations and investments in the development of smallholder farming, where those most vulnerable to price volatility are found. Expanding support for farmers’ organisations would appear to be essential in those sectors undergoing production and market adjustments, where the EU has major dedicated financial assistance programmes in operation (e.g. in the banana and sugar sectors).</p><p>The proposals for the regulation of speculative investment on agricultural commodity market issues relate primarily to information gathering and the formalisation of trading operations within an EU regulatory framework. The extent and nature of the actual regulations to be set in place to ease speculative pressures on agricultural commodity markets has still to be determined.</p><p>The EC’s reference to ‘improved governance and international dialogue’ on actions which ‘affect physical markets and cause price volatility’ could reinforce current EC efforts in the ongoing EPA negotiations to secure commitments to ending the use of export bans and other non-tariff measures to restrict trade. This could become an issue of particular concern to African ACP governments, where export bans are periodically used to ensure national food security in times of high food prices.</p>
		</div>
		
